{"title_page": "President of Venezuela", "text_new": "{{Infobox Political post\n|post            = President\n|body            = the Bolivarian Republic of Venezuela\n|native_name     = {{small|Presidente de la Rep\u00fablica Bolivariana de Venezuela}}\n|insignia        = Presidential Standard of Venezuela.svg{{!}}border\n|insigniacaption = [[List of flags of Venezuela|Presidential Standard of Venezuela]]\n|imagen          = \n|incumbent       = [[2019 Venezuelan presidential crisis|Disputed]]\n|incumbentsince  = \n|style           = [[Mr. President (title)|Mr. President]]<br />({{small|''Se\u00f1or Presidente''}})<br />or<br />[[His Excellency]]\n|memberof        = [[Cabinet of Venezuela|Cabinet]]\n|residence       = [[La Casona]] ([[:es:La Casona (Residencia presidencial)|es]])\n|seat            = [[Miraflores Palace]], [[Caracas]]\n|appointer       = [[2013 Venezuelan presidential election|Popular vote election]]\n|termlength      = Six years<br />{{small|Renewable indefinitely}}\n|salary          = 4,068 USD monthly<ref name=\"latinpost.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.latinpost.com/articles/141919/20170622/comparing-latin-america-s-presidential-salaries-minimum-wage-shocking.htm|title=Shocking Gap Between Latin America\u2019s Presidential Salaries And Workers Minimum Wage|publisher=Latin Post}}</ref>\n|formation       = January 13, 1830\n|inaugural       = [[Crist\u00f3bal Mendoza]] {{small|([[First Republic of Venezuela|First Republic]])}}<br />[[Jos\u00e9 Antonio P\u00e1ez]] {{small|([[State of Venezuela]])}}\n|deputy          = [[Vice President of Venezuela]]\n|website         = [http://www.presidencia.gob.ve/ presidencia.gob.ve]\n}}\n{{Politics of Venezuela}}\nThe '''President of Venezuela''' ({{lang-es|Presidente de Venezuela}}), officially known as the '''President of the Bolivarian Republic of Venezuela''' ({{lang-es|Presidente de la Rep\u00fablica Bolivariana de Venezuela}}), is the [[head of state]] and [[head of government]] in [[Venezuela]]. The president leads the [[Executive (government)|National Executive]] of the [[Government of Venezuela|Venezuelan government]] and is the [[Commander-in-chief#Venezuela|commander-in-chief]] of the [[National Bolivarian Armed Forces of Venezuela|National Bolivarian Armed Forces]]. Presidential terms were set at six years with the adoption of the [[Constitution of Venezuela|1999 Constitution of Venezuela]], and presidential term limits were removed in 2009.<ref name=termlimits/>\n\nThe office of president in Venezuela has existed since the 1811 [[Venezuelan Declaration of Independence]] from the [[Spanish Crown]]; the first president was [[Crist\u00f3bal Mendoza]]. From 1821 to 1830, Venezuela was a member state of [[Gran Colombia]], and the Venezuelan executive was absorbed by the Colombian government in [[Bogot\u00e1]]. When the [[History of Venezuela (1830\u20131908)|State of Venezuela]] became independent from Gran Colombia, the office of the president was restored under [[Jos\u00e9 Antonio P\u00e1ez]]. Every head of state of Venezuela since then has held the title of president.\n\nAs of November, the [[Venezuelan presidential crisis]] is unresolved and who holds the office is disputed since 10 January 2019, when the opposition-majority [[National Assembly (Venezuela)|National Assembly]] declared that incumbent [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]]'s [[2018 Venezuelan presidential election|2018 re-election]] was invalid and the body declared its president, [[Juan Guaid\u00f3]], to be [[acting president]] of the country.<ref name=\"bbc.com\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/mundo/noticias-america-latina-46952641|title=El Tribunal Supremo de Justicia de Venezuela declara \"inconstitucional\" a la Asamblea Nacional y anula el nombramiento de Juan Guaid\u00f3 como su presidente|accessdate=29 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Powers==\n[[File:Standard President of Venezuela.png|thumb|150px|Presidential Standard. (''In Land'')]]\n[[File:Presidential Standard of Venezuela(at Sea).svg|thumb|150px|Presidential Standard. (''At Sea'')]]\nAs a self described republic with a presidential executive, Venezuela grants significant powers to the president. He or she effectively controls the executive branch, represents the country abroad, and appoints the cabinet and, with the approval of the [[National Assembly (Venezuela)|National Assembly]], the judges for the [[Supreme Tribunal of Justice (Venezuela)|Supreme Tribunal of Justice]]. The president is also the [[commander-in-chief]] of the [[National Bolivarian Armed Forces of Venezuela|National Bolivarian Armed Forces]] (FANB).\n\nThe powers and obligations of the President of Venezuela are established, limited and numbered by articles 236 and 237 of the [[Constitution of Venezuela|constitution]]:\n# To comply with and enforce the Constitution and the law.\n# To direct the activity of the Government.\n# To appoint and remove the [[Vice President of Venezuela|Executive Vice-President]] and the [[Cabinet of Venezuela|Cabinet Ministers]].\n# To direct the international relations of the Republic and sign and ratify international treaties, agreements or conventions.\n# To direct the National Armed Forces in his capacity as Commander-in-Chief, exercise supreme hierarchical Authority over the same and establish their contingent. \n# To exercise supreme command over the National Armed Forces, promote their officers at the rank of colonel or naval captain and above, and appoint them to the positions exclusively reserved to them.\n# To declare states of exception and order the restriction of guarantees in the cases provided for under the Constitution.\n# To issue executive orders having the force of law, subject to authorization in advance by an enabling act.\n# To call special sessions of the National Assembly.\n# To issue regulations for the application of laws, in whole or in part, without altering the spirit, purpose and reason for being of the laws.\n# To administer the National Public Treasury.\n# To negotiate national loans.\n# To order extraordinary budget item in addition to the budget, subject to authorization in advance from the National Assembly or the Delegated Committee.\n# To enter into contracts in the national interest, subject to this Constitution and applicable laws.\n# To designate, subject to prior authorization from the National Assembly or the Delegated Committee, the Attorney-General of the Republic and the heads of the permanent diplomatic missions.\n# To designate and remove those officials whose appointment is made subject to his discretion by the Constitution or the applicable law.\n# To address reports or special messages to the National Assembly, either in person or through the Executive Vice-President.\n# To formulate the National Development Plan and, subject to approval in advance from the National Assembly, direct the implementation of the same.\n# To grant pardons.\n# To determine the number, organization and competence of the Ministries and other organs comprising the National Public Administrative Branch, as well as the organization and functions of the Cabinet Ministers, within the principles and guidelines set forth in the pertinent organic law. \n# To dissolve the National Assembly in the case contemplated by the Constitution.\n# To call reference in the cases provided for under the present Constitution.\n# To call and preside over meetings of the National Defense Council.\n# Any others vested in the President under the Constitution and law.\n\n===Complements and compensations===\nThe President's salary directly derives from the National Treasury, as stated in the Organic Law of Salaries, Pensions and Retirements of High Officials of the Public Power. During his or her tenure, the President may not be employed by anyone else, nor receive any other salary from the state. The President's salary is not to be superior to twelve monthly [[minimum wage]]s,<ref name=ley-salario/> that is to say, 67,469.76 [[Venezuelan bol\u00edvar|VEF]] (as of February 2015).<ref name=15porciento/>\n\nThe {{ill|Presidential Honor Guard Brigade|es|Guardia de Honor Presidencial de Venezuela}} of Venezuela is in charge of the President's protection, as well as the presidential family and their political peers. The Presidential Guard of Honor is made up of members from the four service branches of the National Bolivarian Armed Forces and other institutions of public security, and is headed by a general or flag officer.\n\nSince 1900, the official workplace of the President is the [[Miraflores Palace|Palace of Miraflores]] in [[Caracas]]. The presidential residence has been the palace of La Casona since 1964, instituted by president [[Ra\u00fal Leoni]]. La Casona was  not used by previous President [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro|Maduro]], who has decided not to inhabit it.<ref name=lacasona/>\n\n<gallery class=\"center\" caption=\"Presidential Palaces\" widths=\"150px\">\nFile:Entrada Miraflores.JPG|[[Miraflores Palace]]\nFile:Residencia presidencial la casona.jpg|[[:es:La Casona|La Casona]]\n</gallery>\n\n==History==\n[[File:President Mendoza.jpg|thumb|right|[[Crist\u00f3bal Mendoza]], first President of Venezuela. Painting by [[Mart\u00edn Tovar y Tovar]].]]\nThe presidential designation encompasses only those persons who were sworn into office as President of Venezuela following [[Venezuelan Declaration of Independence|Venezuela's declaration of independence]] from [[Spanish Empire|Spanish colonial rule]], which took effect on July 5, 1811. The first president, taking office on July 5, 1811, was actually the president of a [[triumvirate]] of the [[First Republic of Venezuela|first established Republic of Venezuela]] that rotated the presidency weekly. The person serving as president during the week of July 5 was one of the three signatories of the Declaration of Independence: [[Crist\u00f3bal Mendoza]]. Mendoza shared the triumvirate with Juan Escalona and Baltasar Padr\u00f3n. A second [[triumvirate]] followed on April 3, 1812 whose members were Francisco Espejo, Fernando Toro and Francisco Javier Ustariz.<ref>{{in lang|es}} {{cite web|title=Presidentes de Venezuela|url=http://www.consulvenbucaramanga.com/presidentes.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020805034603/http://www.consulvenbucaramanga.com/presidentes.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=2002-08-05|publisher=Consulado General de Bucaramanga}}</ref><ref>Brice\u00f1o Perozo, Mario. \"Mendoza, Crist\u00f3bal de\" in ''Diccionario de Historia de Venezuela'', Vol. 3. Caracas: Fundaci\u00f3n Polar, 1999. {{ISBN|978-980-6397-37-8}}.</ref>\n\nOwing to the profound confusion of the [[Venezuelan War of Independence]] and the period of [[Gran Colombia]] over what is now Venezuela, this page has gaps between 1813 and 1819. For this period in time, historians refer to the Republic of Venezuela as the [[Second Republic of Venezuela]] (1813\u20131814) and the [[Third Republic of Venezuela]] (1817\u20131819) as [[Simon Bolivar]] twice reestablished the republic. The [[Congress of Angostura]] appointed [[Sim\u00f3n Bol\u00edvar]] \"Supreme Commander of the Republic of Venezuela\" (Jefe Supremo de la Rep\u00fablica de Venezuela) from 1819 until 1830.\n\nIn 1830, [[Jos\u00e9 Antonio P\u00e1ez]] declared Venezuela independent from [[Gran Colombia]] and became president, taking office on January 13, 1830. Although he was not the first president of Venezuela (having in mind [[Crist\u00f3bal Mendoza]] in 1811), he was the first head of state of independent Venezuela, after the dissolution of Gran Colombia. From that point on, five constitutions were adopted, all slightly changing the extent of the President's powers and responsibilities.\n\n==Requirements==\nAccording to articles 227 and 229 of the [[Constitution of Venezuela]], adopted in 1999, the following requirements must be met in order to become President of Venezuela:<ref>Constitution of the Bolivarian Republic of Venezuela, Chapter 11 \u2013 National Executive Power</ref>\n*Being a Venezuelan citizen from birth and possessing no other nationality.\n*Being at least 30 years old at the time of the election.\n*Not being a subject to any conviction by final judgment.\n*Not being a Minister, Governor, Mayor or the Vice President of the Republic from the day the candidacy is announced to the day of the election.\n\n==Term limits==\nThe current presidential term is for six years with the constitutionally guaranteed recourse of holding a popular recall referendum any time within the last three years of a presidential term. A [[2009 Venezuelan constitutional referendum|2009 referendum]] removed the previous restrictions which limited the President to 2 terms.<ref name=termlimits/>\n\nFrom 1958 to 1999, the presidential term was set at five years. A sitting president was not only barred from immediate reelection, but could not run again for 10 years (equivalent to two full terms) after leaving office.\n\n==Recall==\n{{expand section|date=July 2016}}\nThe president may be [[recall election|recalled]] after a specific time in office.\n*[[2004 Venezuelan recall referendum]]\n*[[2016 Venezuelan recall referendum]] (unsuccessful)\n\n==Office-holders==\n{{Main|List of presidents of Venezuela}}\nPresidents of Venezuela who served under the 1864 constitution (starting with [[Juan Cris\u00f3stomo Falc\u00f3n]]) bore the title of \"President of the Union\", instead of the usual \"President of the Republic\" still used today. Aside from that, all heads of state of the country since 1811 have held the title of \"President of Venezuela\", with minor variations regarding the official name of the country (which has changed four times since the restoration of the independence in 1830).\n\n<gallery class=\"center\" caption=\"Living former presidents\">\nFile:Pedrocarmona.jpg|''[[Pedro Carmona]]'' ([[Acting president|Interim]]),<br />served 2002<br /><small>{{birth date and age|1941|7|6|df=y}}</small>\nFile:Diosdado Cabello 2013 cropped.jpg|''[[Diosdado Cabello]]'' ([[Acting president|Interim]]),<br />served 2002<br /><small>{{birth date and age|1963|4|15|df=y}}</small>\n</gallery>\n\n==Latest elections==\n{{main|2018 Venezuelan presidential election}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n!colspan=\"2\"|Candidate\n!Party\n!Votes\n!%\n|-\n|style=\"background:red;\"|\n|align=\"left\"|[[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] || align=\"left\"|[[United Socialist Party of Venezuela]] || 6,244,016 || 67.84\n|-\n|style=\"background:orange;\"|\n|align=\"left\" |[[Henri Falc\u00f3n]] || align=\"left\"|[[Progressive Advance]] || 1,927,174 || 20.93\n|-\n|style=\"background:green;\"|\n|align=\"left\" |[[Javier Bertucci]] || align=\"left\"|Independent || 983,140 || 10.82\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D2691E;\"|\n|align=\"left\" |[[Reinaldo Quijada]] || align=\"left\"|Popular Political Unit 89 || 36,132 || 0.39\n|-\n|colspan=\"3\" align=\"left\"|'''Valid votes''' || 9,203,744 || 98.10\n|-\n|colspan=\"3\" align=\"left\"|Invalid/blank votes || 177,474 || 1.89\n|-\n|colspan=\"3\" align=\"left\"|'''Total''' || '''9,381,218''' || '''100'''\n|-\n|colspan=\"3\" align=\"left\"|Registered voters/turnout || 20,527,571 || 46.07\n|-\n|colspan=\"5\" align=\"left\"|Source: [http://www.cne.gov.ve/ResultadosElecciones2018/index.php National Electoral Commission]\n|}\n\n== 2019 crisis ==\n{{main|2019 Venezuelan presidential crisis}}\n[[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] of the [[United Socialist Party of Venezuela]] (PSUV) entered the office as [[interim president]] on 5 March 2013 after the death of [[Hugo Ch\u00e1vez]], and was elected in the [[2013 Venezuelan presidential election|2013 presidential election]].  He was reelected in the [[2018 Venezuelan presidential election|2018 presidential election]], which was disputed amid charges of irregularities including: the elections were held four months before the prescribed date,<ref name=\"BBCweighs\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-42984448|title=Venezuela opposition weighs election run|date=8 February 2018|work=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=8 February 2018}}</ref> multiple major opposition parties were banned from participating or imprisoned,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.el-nacional.com/noticias/gobierno/anc-aprobo-decreto-para-validacion-los-partidos-politicos_216253|title=ANC aprob\u00f3 un decreto para la validaci\u00f3n de los partidos pol\u00edticos|date=20 December 2017|website=El Nacional}}<br />* {{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/mundo/noticias-america-latina-46805683|title=Por qu\u00e9 es pol\u00e9mico que Maduro jure como presidente de Venezuela y por qu\u00e9 lo hace ahora si las elecciones fueron en mayo|last=Olmo (@BBCgolmo)|first=Guillermo D.|date=10 January 2019|work=BBC News Mundo|access-date=11 January 2019}}<br />* {{cite web|url=http://efectococuyo.com/politica/maduro-gana-con-la-abstencion-historica-mas-alta-en-comicios-presidenciales/|title=Maduro gana con la abstenci\u00f3n hist\u00f3rica m\u00e1s alta en comicios presidenciales - Efecto Cocuyo|website=efectococuyo.com|access-date=11 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181221101748/http://efectococuyo.com/politica/maduro-gana-con-la-abstencion-historica-mas-alta-en-comicios-presidenciales/|archive-date=21 December 2018|url-status=live}}<br />* {{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-42304594|title=Venezuela opposition banned from running in 2018 election|date=11 December 2017|work=[[BBC News]]}}</ref> and there were charges of vote-buying.<ref>{{cite web\n|title      = Maduro eyes re-election as Venezuela fires starting gun for presidential vote\n|url        = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jan/23/venezuela-presidential-election-likely-before-end-of-april\n|publisher  = [[The Guardian]]\n|accessdate = 7 February 2019\n|date       = 23 January 2018\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n|title      = Venezuela's Maduro re-elected amid outcry over vote\n|url        = https://www.reuters.com/article/us-venezuela-election/venezuelas-maduro-re-elected-amid-outcry-over-vote-idUSKCN1IL05U\n|work  = [[Reuters]]\n|accessdate = 7 February 2019\n|date       = 20 May 2018\n}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 January 2019, the [[National Assembly (Venezuela)|National Assembly]] declared that\u2014following the expiration of the mandate granted through the [[2013 Venezuelan presidential election|2013 presidential election]]\u2014Maduro would have no constitutional mandate to govern Venezuela if he was [[Second inauguration of Nicol\u00e1s Maduro|sworn in on 10 January]].<ref>{{cite web\n|title      = Venezuela's parliament rejects legitimacy of Maduro second term\n|url        = https://www.straitstimes.com/world/americas/venezuelas-parliament-rejects-legitimacy-of-maduro-second-term\n|publisher  = [[The Straits Times]]\n|accessdate = 28 January 2019\n|date       = 6 January 2019\n}}</ref> Article 233 of the Venezuelan Constitution establishes that in the event of a presidential vacuum, the President of the National Assembly takes charge of the presidency until a new election is called within 30 days. Noting that the 2018 presidential election failed to adhere to constitutional requirements, the National Assembly contend that Maduro's second term never began, and the seat is vacant.<ref name=\"Euronews\" />\n\nOn 11 January, [[Juan Guaid\u00f3]] of the [[Popular Will]] party and President of the legislature stated that he was prepared to take on the role of acting President.<ref>{{cite web\n|title      = Maduro foe says he\u2019s ready to replace the president\n|url        = https://www.apnews.com/59c8725090af443db92692c843d2d814\n|first      = Scott\n|last       = Smith\n|publisher  = [[Associated Press]]\n|accessdate = 24 February 2019\n|date       = 12 January 2019\n}}</ref> With the National Assembly recognizing a vacuum in the office of the President,<ref>{{cite web\n|title      = Update 3-Venezuela Congress declares President Maduro 'usurper' of democracy\n|url        = https://www.cnbc.com/2019/01/15/reuters-america-update-3-venezuela-congress-declares-president-maduro-usurper-of-democracy.html\n|first1     = Mayela\n|last1      = Armas\n|first2     = Corina\n|last2      = Pons\n|publisher  = [[CNBC]]\n|accessdate = 24 February 2019\n|date       = 15 January 2019\n}}</ref> and citing Article 233 of the Venezuelan Constitution,<ref name=\"Euronews\" /> Guaid\u00f3 was declared acting President of Venezuela by that body on 16 January.<ref name=\"Euronews\">{{cite web\n|title      = Is it legal for Juan Guaid\u00f3 to be proclaimed Venezuela's interim president?\n|url        = https://www.euronews.com/2019/01/27/is-it-legal-for-juan-guaido-to-be-proclaimed-venezuela-s-interim-president\n|publisher  = [[Euronews]]\n|first      = Camille\n|last       = Bello\n|accessdate = 28 January 2019\n|date       = 27 January 2019\n}}</ref> The legislature approved the [[Statute Governing the Transition to Democracy|Statute Governing the Transition to Democracy to Re-establish the Validity of the Constitution of the Bolivarian Republic of Venezuela]] ({{lang-es|Estatuto que Rige la Transici\u00f3n a la Democracia para Restablecer la Vigencia de la Constituci\u00f3n de la Rep\u00fablica Bolivariana De Venezuela}}) on 5 February, defining the timing of the transition.<ref name= ElNacional8Feb>{{cite news |url= http://www.el-nacional.com/noticias/politica/estatuto-que-rige-transicion-entro-vigencia-martes_269938 |title= El estatuto que rige la transici\u00f3n entr\u00f3 en vigencia el martes |trans-title= The statute governing the transition took effect on Tuesday |language= es |work= El Nacional |date= 8 February 2019 |accessdate= 9 March 2019 | author= Brito, Estefani}}</ref>\n\nMaduro's controversial win and Guaid\u00f3's subsequent claim triggered the [[2019 Venezuelan presidential crisis]]. The international community is divided on the issue of the Venezuelan presidency;<ref>{{cite news |url= https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-venezuela-politics-maduro-guaido-fact/factbox-guaido-vs-maduro-who-backs-venezuelas-two-presidents-idUKKCN1PI1LH |title= Guaido vs Maduro: Who backs Venezuela's two presidents? |work= Reuters |date= 24 January 2019 |accessdate= 5 February 2019}}</ref> ''AP News'' reported that \"familiar geopolitical sides\" had formed, with allies Russia, China, Iran, Syria, and Cuba supporting Maduro, and the US, Canada, and most of Western Europe supporting Guaid\u00f3.<ref name= FamiliarGeo>{{cite news |url= https://www.apnews.com/6b7fa7cc566f486cb974362168f1d90d |title= Venezuela crisis: Familiar geopolitical sides take shape |author= Vasilyeva, Nataliya |date = 24 January 2019 | accessdate= 25 February 2019 |work= AP News}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Venezuela|Politics}}\n*[[List of Presidents of Venezuela]]\n*[[List of Vice Presidents of Venezuela]]\n*[[History of Venezuela]]\n*[[Politics of Venezuela]]\n\n==References==\n{{noteslist}}\n{{reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=termlimits>{{cite news\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/7891856.stm\n|title=Chavez wins chance of fresh term\n|work=[[BBC News Online]]\n|date=16 February 2009\n|language=Spanish\n|location=Caracas\n|accessdate=2 January 2016\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=lacasona>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.noticiascandela.informe25.com/2013/12/presidente-maduro-aclaro-rumores-sobre.html\n|title=Presidente Maduro aclar\u00f3 rumores sobre presencia de familia Ch\u00e1vez en La Casona\n|work=Noticias Candela\n|date=6 December 2013\n|language=Spanish\n|location=\n|accessdate=3 January 2016\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=ley-salario>{{cite news\n |url         = http://www.mp.gob.ve/c/document_library/get_file?p_l_id=10240&folderId=156025&name=DLFE-2227.pdf\n |title       = Ley Org\u00e1nica de Emolumentos, Pensiones y Jubilaciones de los Altos Funcionarios del Poder P\u00fablico\n |work        = Official Gazette of the Bolivarian Republic of Venezuela\n |date        = 12 January 2011\n |language    = Spanish\n |location    = Caracas\n |accessdate  = 3 January 2016\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20161230002339/http://www.mp.gob.ve/c/document_library/get_file?p_l_id=10240&folderId=156025&name=DLFE-2227.pdf\n |archivedate = 30 December 2016\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=15porciento>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.eluniversal.com/economia/150209/oficializan-aumento-de-15-del-salario-minimo\n|title=Oficializan aumento de 15% del salario m\u00ednimo\n|work=[[El Universal (Caracas)|El Universal]]\n|date=9 February 2015\n|language=Spanish\n|location=Caracas\n|accessdate=3 January 2016\n}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.presidencia.gob.ve/Site/Web/Principal/paginas/classIndex.php Official website of the Presidency of Venezuela] {{in lang|es}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110902002326/http://www.gobiernoenlinea.ve/misc-view/index.pag Official website of the Venezuelan Government] {{in lang|es}}\n\n{{Venezuela topics}}\n{{Presidents of Venezuela}}\n{{Heads of State of the South America}}\n\n[[Category:Presidents of Venezuela| ]]\n[[Category:1830 establishments in Venezuela]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Political post\n|post            = President\n|body            = the Bolivarian Republic of Venezuela\n|native_name     = {{small|Presidente de la Rep\u00fablica Bolivariana de Venezuela}}\n|insignia        = Presidential Standard of Venezuela.svg{{!}}border\n|insigniacaption = [[List of flags of Venezuela|Presidential Standard of Venezuela]]\n|imagen          = \n|incumbent       = [[2019 Venezuelan presidential crisis|Disputed]]\n|incumbentsince  = \n|style           = [[Mr. President (title)|Mr. President]]<br />({{small|''Se\u00f1or Presidente''}})<br />or<br />[[His Excellency]]\n|memberof        = [[Cabinet of Venezuela|Cabinet]]\n|residence       = [[La Casona]] ([[:es:La Casona (Residencia presidencial)|es]])\n|seat            = [[Miraflores Palace]], [[Caracas]]\n|appointer       = [[2013 Venezuelan presidential election|Popular vote election]]\n|termlength      = Six years<br />{{small|Renewable indefinitely}}\n|salary          = 4,068 USD monthly<ref name=\"latinpost.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.latinpost.com/articles/141919/20170622/comparing-latin-america-s-presidential-salaries-minimum-wage-shocking.htm|title=Shocking Gap Between Latin America\u2019s Presidential Salaries And Workers Minimum Wage|publisher=Latin Post}}</ref>\n|formation       = January 13, 1830\n|inaugural       = [[Crist\u00f3bal Mendoza]] {{small|([[First Republic of Venezuela|First Republic]])}}<br />[[Jos\u00e9 Antonio P\u00e1ez]] {{small|([[State of Venezuela]])}}\n|deputy          = [[Vice President of Venezuela]]\n|website         = [http://www.presidencia.gob.ve/ presidencia.gob.ve]\n}}\n{{Politics of Venezuela}}\nThe '''President of Venezuela''' ({{lang-es|Presidente de Venezuela}}), officially known as the '''President of the Bolivarian Republic of Venezuela''' ({{lang-es|Presidente de la Rep\u00fablica Bolivariana de Venezuela}}), is the [[head of state]] and [[head of government]] in [[Venezuela]]. The president leads the [[Executive (government)|National Executive]] of the [[Government of Venezuela|Venezuelan government]] and is the [[Commander-in-chief#Venezuela|commander-in-chief]] of the [[National Bolivarian Armed Forces of Venezuela|National Bolivarian Armed Forces]]. Presidential terms were set at six years with the adoption of the [[Constitution of Venezuela|1999 Constitution of Venezuela]], and presidential term limits were removed in 2009.<ref name=termlimits/>\n\nThe office of president in Venezuela has existed since the 1811 [[Venezuelan Declaration of Independence]] from the [[Spanish Crown]]; the first president was [[Crist\u00f3bal Mendoza]]. From 1821 to 1830, Venezuela was a member state of [[Gran Colombia]], and the Venezuelan executive was absorbed by the Colombian government in [[Bogot\u00e1]]. When the [[History of Venezuela (1830\u20131908)|State of Venezuela]] became independent from Gran Colombia, the office of the president was restored under [[Jos\u00e9 Antonio P\u00e1ez]]. Every head of state of Venezuela since then has held the title of president.\n\nAs of November, the [[Venezuelan presidential crisis]] is unresolved and who holds the office is disputed since 10 January 2019, when the opposition-majority [[National Assembly (Venezuela)|National Assembly]] declared that incumbent [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]]'s [[2018 Venezuelan presidential election|2018 re-election]] was invalid and the body declared its president, [[Juan Guaid\u00f3]], to be [[acting president]] of the country.<ref name=\"bbc.com\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/mundo/noticias-america-latina-46952641|title=El Tribunal Supremo de Justicia de Venezuela declara \"inconstitucional\" a la Asamblea Nacional y anula el nombramiento de Juan Guaid\u00f3 como su presidente|accessdate=29 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Powers==\n[[File:Standard President of Venezuela.png|thumb|150px|Presidential Standard. (''In Land'')]]\n[[File:Presidential Standard of Venezuela(at Sea).svg|thumb|150px|Presidential Standard. (''At Sea'')]]\nAs a self described republic with a presidential executive, Venezuela grants significant powers to the president. He or she effectively controls the executive branch, represents the country abroad, and appoints the cabinet and, with the approval of the [[National Assembly (Venezuela)|National Assembly]], the judges for the [[Supreme Tribunal of Justice (Venezuela)|Supreme Tribunal of Justice]]. The president is also the [[commander-in-chief]] of the [[National Bolivarian Armed Forces of Venezuela|National Bolivarian Armed Forces]] (FANB).\n\nThe powers and obligations of the President of Venezuela are established, limited and numbered by articles 236 and 237 of the [[Constitution of Venezuela|constitution]]:\n# To comply with and enforce the Constitution and the law.\n# To direct the activity of the Government.\n# To appoint and remove the [[Vice President of Venezuela|Executive Vice-President]] and the [[Cabinet of Venezuela|Cabinet Ministers]].\n# To direct the international relations of the Republic and sign and ratify international treaties, agreements or conventions.\n# To direct the National Armed Forces in his capacity as Commander-in-Chief, exercise supreme hierarchical Authority over the same and establish their contingent. \n# To exercise supreme command over the National Armed Forces, promote their officers at the rank of colonel or naval captain and above, and appoint them to the positions exclusively reserved to them.\n# To declare states of exception and order the restriction of guarantees in the cases provided for under the Constitution.\n# To issue executive orders having the force of law, subject to authorization in advance by an enabling act.\n# To call special sessions of the National Assembly.\n# To issue regulations for the application of laws, in whole or in part, without altering the spirit, purpose and reason for being of the laws.\n# To administer the National Public Treasury.\n# To negotiate national loans.\n# To order extraordinary budget item in addition to the budget, subject to authorization in advance from the National Assembly or the Delegated Committee.\n# To enter into contracts in the national interest, subject to this Constitution and applicable laws.\n# To designate, subject to prior authorization from the National Assembly or the Delegated Committee, the Attorney-General of the Republic and the heads of the permanent diplomatic missions.\n# To designate and remove those officials whose appointment is made subject to his discretion by the Constitution or the applicable law.\n# To address reports or special messages to the National Assembly, either in person or through the Executive Vice-President.\n# To formulate the National Development Plan and, subject to approval in advance from the National Assembly, direct the implementation of the same.\n# To grant pardons.\n# To determine the number, organization and competence of the Ministries and other organs comprising the National Public Administrative Branch, as well as the organization and functions of the Cabinet Ministers, within the principles and guidelines set forth in the pertinent organic law. \n# To dissolve the National Assembly in the case contemplated by the Constitution.\n# To call reference in the cases provided for under the present Constitution.\n# To call and preside over meetings of the National Defense Council.\n# Any others vested in the President under the Constitution and law.\n\n===Complements and compensations===\nThe President's salary directly derives from the National Treasury, as stated in the Organic Law of Salaries, Pensions and Retirements of High Officials of the Public Power. During his or her tenure, the President may not be employed by anyone else, nor receive any other salary from the state. The President's salary is not to be superior to twelve monthly [[minimum wage]]s,<ref name=ley-salario/> that is to say, 67,469.76 [[Venezuelan bol\u00edvar|VEF]] (as of February 2015).<ref name=15porciento/>\n\nThe {{ill|Presidential Honor Guard Brigade|es|Guardia de Honor Presidencial de Venezuela}} of Venezuela is in charge of the President's protection, as well as the presidential family and their political peers. The Presidential Guard of Honor is made up of members from the four service branches of the National Bolivarian Armed Forces and other institutions of public security, and is headed by a general or flag officer.\n\nSince 1900, the official workplace of the President is the [[Miraflores Palace|Palace of Miraflores]] in [[Caracas]]. The presidential residence has been the palace of La Casona since 1964, instituted by president [[Ra\u00fal Leoni]]. La Casona was  not used by previous President [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro|Maduro]], who has decided not to inhabit it.<ref name=lacasona/>\n\n<gallery class=\"center\" caption=\"Presidential Palaces\" widths=\"150px\">\nFile:Entrada Miraflores.JPG|[[Miraflores Palace]]\nFile:Residencia presidencial la casona.jpg|[[:es:La Casona|La Casona]]\n</gallery>\n\n==History==\n[[File:President Mendoza.jpg|thumb|right|[[Crist\u00f3bal Mendoza]], first President of Venezuela. Painting by [[Mart\u00edn Tovar y Tovar]].]]\nThe presidential designation encompasses only those persons who were sworn into office as President of Venezuela following [[Venezuelan Declaration of Independence|Venezuela's declaration of independence]] from [[Spanish Empire|Spanish colonial rule]], which took effect on July 5, 1811. The first president, taking office on July 5, 1811, was actually the president of a [[triumvirate]] of the [[First Republic of Venezuela|first established Republic of Venezuela]] that rotated the presidency weekly. The person serving as president during the week of July 5 was one of the three signatories of the Declaration of Independence: [[Crist\u00f3bal Mendoza]]. Mendoza shared the triumvirate with Juan Escalona and Baltasar Padr\u00f3n. A second [[triumvirate]] followed on April 3, 1812 whose members were Francisco Espejo, Fernando Toro and Francisco Javier Ustariz.<ref>{{in lang|es}} {{cite web|title=Presidentes de Venezuela|url=http://www.consulvenbucaramanga.com/presidentes.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020805034603/http://www.consulvenbucaramanga.com/presidentes.htm|url-status=dead|archive-date=2002-08-05|publisher=Consulado General de Bucaramanga}}</ref><ref>Brice\u00f1o Perozo, Mario. \"Mendoza, Crist\u00f3bal de\" in ''Diccionario de Historia de Venezuela'', Vol. 3. Caracas: Fundaci\u00f3n Polar, 1999. {{ISBN|978-980-6397-37-8}}.</ref>\n\nOwing to the profound confusion of the [[Venezuelan War of Independence]] and the period of [[Gran Colombia]] over what is now Venezuela, this page has gaps between 1813 and 1819. For this period in time, historians refer to the Republic of Venezuela as the [[Second Republic of Venezuela]] (1813\u20131814) and the [[Third Republic of Venezuela]] (1817\u20131819) as [[Simon Bolivar]] twice reestablished the republic. The [[Congress of Angostura]] appointed [[Sim\u00f3n Bol\u00edvar]] \"Supreme Commander of the Republic of Venezuela\" (Jefe Supremo de la Rep\u00fablica de Venezuela) from 1819 until 1830.\n\nIn 1830, [[Jos\u00e9 Antonio P\u00e1ez]] declared Venezuela independent from [[Gran Colombia]] and became president, taking office on January 13, 1830. Although he was not the first president of Venezuela (having in mind [[Crist\u00f3bal Mendoza]] in 1811), he was the first head of state of independent Venezuela, after the dissolution of Gran Colombia. From that point on, five constitutions were adopted, all slightly changing the extent of the President's powers and responsibilities.\n\n==Requirements==\nAccording to articles 227 and 229 of the [[Constitution of Venezuela]], adopted in 1999, the following requirements must be met in order to become President of Venezuela:<ref>Constitution of the Bolivarian Republic of Venezuela, Chapter 11 \u2013 National Executive Power</ref>\n*Being a Venezuelan citizen from birth and possessing no other nationality.\n*Being at least 30 years old at the time of the election.\n*Not being a subject to any conviction by final judgment.\n*Not being a Minister, Governor, Mayor or the Vice President of the Republic from the day the candidacy is announced to the day of the election.\n\n==Term limits==\nThe current presidential term is for six years with the constitutionally guaranteed recourse of holding a popular recall referendum any time within the last three years of a presidential term. A [[2009 Venezuelan constitutional referendum|2009 referendum]] removed the previous restrictions which limited the President to 2 terms.<ref name=termlimits/>\n\nFrom 1958 to 1999, the presidential term was set at five years. A sitting president was not only barred from immediate reelection, but could not run again for 10 years (equivalent to two full terms) after leaving office.\n\n==Recall==\n{{expand section|date=July 2016}}\nThe president may be [[recall election|recalled]] after a specific time in office.\n*[[2004 Venezuelan recall referendum]]\n*[[2016 Venezuelan recall referendum]] (unsucessful)\n\n==Office-holders==\n{{Main|List of presidents of Venezuela}}\nPresidents of Venezuela who served under the 1864 constitution (starting with [[Juan Cris\u00f3stomo Falc\u00f3n]]) bore the title of \"President of the Union\", instead of the usual \"President of the Republic\" still used today. Aside from that, all heads of state of the country since 1811 have held the title of \"President of Venezuela\", with minor variations regarding the official name of the country (which has changed four times since the restoration of the independence in 1830).\n\n<gallery class=\"center\" caption=\"Living former presidents\">\nFile:Pedrocarmona.jpg|''[[Pedro Carmona]]'' ([[Acting president|Interim]]),<br />served 2002<br /><small>{{birth date and age|1941|7|6|df=y}}</small>\nFile:Diosdado Cabello 2013 cropped.jpg|''[[Diosdado Cabello]]'' ([[Acting president|Interim]]),<br />served 2002<br /><small>{{birth date and age|1963|4|15|df=y}}</small>\n</gallery>\n\n==Latest elections==\n{{main|2018 Venezuelan presidential election}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n!colspan=\"2\"|Candidate\n!Party\n!Votes\n!%\n|-\n|style=\"background:red;\"|\n|align=\"left\"|[[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] || align=\"left\"|[[United Socialist Party of Venezuela]] || 6,244,016 || 67.84\n|-\n|style=\"background:orange;\"|\n|align=\"left\" |[[Henri Falc\u00f3n]] || align=\"left\"|[[Progressive Advance]] || 1,927,174 || 20.93\n|-\n|style=\"background:green;\"|\n|align=\"left\" |[[Javier Bertucci]] || align=\"left\"|Independent || 983,140 || 10.82\n|-\n|style=\"background:#D2691E;\"|\n|align=\"left\" |[[Reinaldo Quijada]] || align=\"left\"|Popular Political Unit 89 || 36,132 || 0.39\n|-\n|colspan=\"3\" align=\"left\"|'''Valid votes''' || 9,203,744 || 98.10\n|-\n|colspan=\"3\" align=\"left\"|Invalid/blank votes || 177,474 || 1.89\n|-\n|colspan=\"3\" align=\"left\"|'''Total''' || '''9,381,218''' || '''100'''\n|-\n|colspan=\"3\" align=\"left\"|Registered voters/turnout || 20,527,571 || 46.07\n|-\n|colspan=\"5\" align=\"left\"|Source: [http://www.cne.gov.ve/ResultadosElecciones2018/index.php National Electoral Commission]\n|}\n\n== 2019 crisis ==\n{{main|2019 Venezuelan presidential crisis}}\n[[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] of the [[United Socialist Party of Venezuela]] (PSUV) entered the office as [[interim president]] on 5 March 2013 after the death of [[Hugo Ch\u00e1vez]], and was elected in the [[2013 Venezuelan presidential election|2013 presidential election]].  He was reelected in the [[2018 Venezuelan presidential election|2018 presidential election]], which was disputed amid charges of irregularities including: the elections were held four months before the prescribed date,<ref name=\"BBCweighs\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-42984448|title=Venezuela opposition weighs election run|date=8 February 2018|work=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=8 February 2018}}</ref> multiple major opposition parties were banned from participating or imprisoned,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.el-nacional.com/noticias/gobierno/anc-aprobo-decreto-para-validacion-los-partidos-politicos_216253|title=ANC aprob\u00f3 un decreto para la validaci\u00f3n de los partidos pol\u00edticos|date=20 December 2017|website=El Nacional}}<br />* {{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/mundo/noticias-america-latina-46805683|title=Por qu\u00e9 es pol\u00e9mico que Maduro jure como presidente de Venezuela y por qu\u00e9 lo hace ahora si las elecciones fueron en mayo|last=Olmo (@BBCgolmo)|first=Guillermo D.|date=10 January 2019|work=BBC News Mundo|access-date=11 January 2019}}<br />* {{cite web|url=http://efectococuyo.com/politica/maduro-gana-con-la-abstencion-historica-mas-alta-en-comicios-presidenciales/|title=Maduro gana con la abstenci\u00f3n hist\u00f3rica m\u00e1s alta en comicios presidenciales - Efecto Cocuyo|website=efectococuyo.com|access-date=11 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181221101748/http://efectococuyo.com/politica/maduro-gana-con-la-abstencion-historica-mas-alta-en-comicios-presidenciales/|archive-date=21 December 2018|url-status=live}}<br />* {{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-42304594|title=Venezuela opposition banned from running in 2018 election|date=11 December 2017|work=[[BBC News]]}}</ref> and there were charges of vote-buying.<ref>{{cite web\n|title      = Maduro eyes re-election as Venezuela fires starting gun for presidential vote\n|url        = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/jan/23/venezuela-presidential-election-likely-before-end-of-april\n|publisher  = [[The Guardian]]\n|accessdate = 7 February 2019\n|date       = 23 January 2018\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n|title      = Venezuela's Maduro re-elected amid outcry over vote\n|url        = https://www.reuters.com/article/us-venezuela-election/venezuelas-maduro-re-elected-amid-outcry-over-vote-idUSKCN1IL05U\n|work  = [[Reuters]]\n|accessdate = 7 February 2019\n|date       = 20 May 2018\n}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 January 2019, the [[National Assembly (Venezuela)|National Assembly]] declared that\u2014following the expiration of the mandate granted through the [[2013 Venezuelan presidential election|2013 presidential election]]\u2014Maduro would have no constitutional mandate to govern Venezuela if he was [[Second inauguration of Nicol\u00e1s Maduro|sworn in on 10 January]].<ref>{{cite web\n|title      = Venezuela's parliament rejects legitimacy of Maduro second term\n|url        = https://www.straitstimes.com/world/americas/venezuelas-parliament-rejects-legitimacy-of-maduro-second-term\n|publisher  = [[The Straits Times]]\n|accessdate = 28 January 2019\n|date       = 6 January 2019\n}}</ref> Article 233 of the Venezuelan Constitution establishes that in the event of a presidential vacuum, the President of the National Assembly takes charge of the presidency until a new election is called within 30 days. Noting that the 2018 presidential election failed to adhere to constitutional requirements, the National Assembly contend that Maduro's second term never began, and the seat is vacant.<ref name=\"Euronews\" />\n\nOn 11 January, [[Juan Guaid\u00f3]] of the [[Popular Will]] party and President of the legislature stated that he was prepared to take on the role of acting President.<ref>{{cite web\n|title      = Maduro foe says he\u2019s ready to replace the president\n|url        = https://www.apnews.com/59c8725090af443db92692c843d2d814\n|first      = Scott\n|last       = Smith\n|publisher  = [[Associated Press]]\n|accessdate = 24 February 2019\n|date       = 12 January 2019\n}}</ref> With the National Assembly recognizing a vacuum in the office of the President,<ref>{{cite web\n|title      = Update 3-Venezuela Congress declares President Maduro 'usurper' of democracy\n|url        = https://www.cnbc.com/2019/01/15/reuters-america-update-3-venezuela-congress-declares-president-maduro-usurper-of-democracy.html\n|first1     = Mayela\n|last1      = Armas\n|first2     = Corina\n|last2      = Pons\n|publisher  = [[CNBC]]\n|accessdate = 24 February 2019\n|date       = 15 January 2019\n}}</ref> and citing Article 233 of the Venezuelan Constitution,<ref name=\"Euronews\" /> Guaid\u00f3 was declared acting President of Venezuela by that body on 16 January.<ref name=\"Euronews\">{{cite web\n|title      = Is it legal for Juan Guaid\u00f3 to be proclaimed Venezuela's interim president?\n|url        = https://www.euronews.com/2019/01/27/is-it-legal-for-juan-guaido-to-be-proclaimed-venezuela-s-interim-president\n|publisher  = [[Euronews]]\n|first      = Camille\n|last       = Bello\n|accessdate = 28 January 2019\n|date       = 27 January 2019\n}}</ref> The legislature approved the [[Statute Governing the Transition to Democracy|Statute Governing the Transition to Democracy to Re-establish the Validity of the Constitution of the Bolivarian Republic of Venezuela]] ({{lang-es|Estatuto que Rige la Transici\u00f3n a la Democracia para Restablecer la Vigencia de la Constituci\u00f3n de la Rep\u00fablica Bolivariana De Venezuela}}) on 5 February, defining the timing of the transition.<ref name= ElNacional8Feb>{{cite news |url= http://www.el-nacional.com/noticias/politica/estatuto-que-rige-transicion-entro-vigencia-martes_269938 |title= El estatuto que rige la transici\u00f3n entr\u00f3 en vigencia el martes |trans-title= The statute governing the transition took effect on Tuesday |language= es |work= El Nacional |date= 8 February 2019 |accessdate= 9 March 2019 | author= Brito, Estefani}}</ref>\n\nMaduro's controversial win and Guaid\u00f3's subsequent claim triggered the [[2019 Venezuelan presidential crisis]]. The international community is divided on the issue of the Venezuelan presidency;<ref>{{cite news |url= https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-venezuela-politics-maduro-guaido-fact/factbox-guaido-vs-maduro-who-backs-venezuelas-two-presidents-idUKKCN1PI1LH |title= Guaido vs Maduro: Who backs Venezuela's two presidents? |work= Reuters |date= 24 January 2019 |accessdate= 5 February 2019}}</ref> ''AP News'' reported that \"familiar geopolitical sides\" had formed, with allies Russia, China, Iran, Syria, and Cuba supporting Maduro, and the US, Canada, and most of Western Europe supporting Guaid\u00f3.<ref name= FamiliarGeo>{{cite news |url= https://www.apnews.com/6b7fa7cc566f486cb974362168f1d90d |title= Venezuela crisis: Familiar geopolitical sides take shape |author= Vasilyeva, Nataliya |date = 24 January 2019 | accessdate= 25 February 2019 |work= AP News}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Venezuela|Politics}}\n*[[List of Presidents of Venezuela]]\n*[[List of Vice Presidents of Venezuela]]\n*[[History of Venezuela]]\n*[[Politics of Venezuela]]\n\n==References==\n{{noteslist}}\n{{reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=termlimits>{{cite news\n|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/7891856.stm\n|title=Chavez wins chance of fresh term\n|work=[[BBC News Online]]\n|date=16 February 2009\n|language=Spanish\n|location=Caracas\n|accessdate=2 January 2016\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=lacasona>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.noticiascandela.informe25.com/2013/12/presidente-maduro-aclaro-rumores-sobre.html\n|title=Presidente Maduro aclar\u00f3 rumores sobre presencia de familia Ch\u00e1vez en La Casona\n|work=Noticias Candela\n|date=6 December 2013\n|language=Spanish\n|location=\n|accessdate=3 January 2016\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=ley-salario>{{cite news\n |url         = http://www.mp.gob.ve/c/document_library/get_file?p_l_id=10240&folderId=156025&name=DLFE-2227.pdf\n |title       = Ley Org\u00e1nica de Emolumentos, Pensiones y Jubilaciones de los Altos Funcionarios del Poder P\u00fablico\n |work        = Official Gazette of the Bolivarian Republic of Venezuela\n |date        = 12 January 2011\n |language    = Spanish\n |location    = Caracas\n |accessdate  = 3 January 2016\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20161230002339/http://www.mp.gob.ve/c/document_library/get_file?p_l_id=10240&folderId=156025&name=DLFE-2227.pdf\n |archivedate = 30 December 2016\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=15porciento>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.eluniversal.com/economia/150209/oficializan-aumento-de-15-del-salario-minimo\n|title=Oficializan aumento de 15% del salario m\u00ednimo\n|work=[[El Universal (Caracas)|El Universal]]\n|date=9 February 2015\n|language=Spanish\n|location=Caracas\n|accessdate=3 January 2016\n}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.presidencia.gob.ve/Site/Web/Principal/paginas/classIndex.php Official website of the Presidency of Venezuela] {{in lang|es}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110902002326/http://www.gobiernoenlinea.ve/misc-view/index.pag Official website of the Venezuelan Government] {{in lang|es}}\n\n{{Venezuela topics}}\n{{Presidents of Venezuela}}\n{{Heads of State of the South America}}\n\n[[Category:Presidents of Venezuela| ]]\n[[Category:1830 establishments in Venezuela]]\n", "name_user": "Nat965", "label": "safe", "comment":