n)\n| last_election7 = 19 seats, 5.4%\n| seats_before7 = 19\n| seat_change7 = {{increase}} 1\n| seats7 = 20\n| leaders_seat7 = [[Stockholm County]]\n| popular_vote7 = 355,546\n| percentage7 = 5.5%\n| swing7 = {{increase}} 0.1[[percentage point|pp]]\n| image8 = [[File:Isabella L\u00f6vin signing climate law referral (cropped).jpg|85x85px]]<br />[[File:Almedalen 2017 (36197325382) (cropped).jpg|85x85px]]\n| colour8 = \n| leader8 = [[Isabella L\u00f6vin]]<br />[[Gustav Fridolin]]\n| leader_since8 = 13 May 2016<br/>21 May 2011\n| party8 = Green Party (Sweden)\n| alliance8 = [[L\u00f6fven I Cabinet|L\u00f6fven Cabinet]]<br />([[Red-Greens (Sweden)|Red-Greens]])\n| last_election8 = 25 seats, 6.9%\n| seats_before8 = 25\n| seats8 = 16\n| leaders_seat8 = \u2014\n| seat_change8 = {{decrease}} 9\n| popular_vote8 = 285,899\n| percentage8 = 4.4%\n| swing8 = {{decrease}} 2.5[[percentage point|pp]]\n<!-- Map -->| map_image = Swedish_General_Election_2018.svg\n| map_size = 400px\n| map_caption = Largest party by district (left) and municipality (right) Red \u2013 Social Democratic, Blue \u2013 Moderate, Yellow \u2013 Sweden Democrats\n<!--PM before/after-->| title = [[Prime Minister of Sweden|Prime Minister]]\n| posttitle = \n| before_election = [[Stefan L\u00f6fven]]\n| before_party = Swedish Social Democratic Party\n| after_election = [[Stefan L\u00f6fven]]\n| after_party = Swedish Social Democratic Party\n| elected_members = List of members of the Riksdag, 2018\u20132022\n| outgoing_members = List of members of the Riksdag, 2014\u201318\n}}\n\n'''General elections''' were held in [[Sweden]] on Sunday 9 September 2018 to elect the 349 members of the [[Riksdag]]. Regional and municipal elections were also held on the same day. The incumbent minority government, consisting of the [[Swedish Social Democratic Party|Social Democrats]] and the [[Green Party (Sweden)|Greens]] and supported by the [[Left Party (Sweden)|Left Party]], won 144 seats, one seat more than the four-party [[Alliance (Sweden)|Alliance coalition]], with the [[Sweden Democrats]] winning the remaining 62 seats. The Social Democrats' vote share fell to 28.3 percent, its lowest level of support [[1911 Swedish general election|since 1911]], although the main opposition, the [[Moderate Party|Moderates]], lost even more support. The Sweden Democrats made gains, though less than anticipated.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/europe/sweden-faces-hung-parliament-as-far-right-makes-huge-gains-1.3623956|title=Sweden faces hung parliament as far-right makes big gains|newspaper=Irish Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2018/sep/09/sweden-election-live|title=Swedish election: deadlock for main parties as far right makes gains \u2013 as it happened|first1=Kate Lyons|last1=(now)|first2=Patrick Greenfield|last2=(earlier)|first3=Patrick|last3=Greenfield|date=9 September 2018|newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/global-opinions/wp/2018/09/10/swedens-election-represents-the-new-normal-of-european-politics/|title=Opinion - Sweden's election represents the new normal of European politics|last=Carl Bildt|newspaper=Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/09/10/reuters-america-forex-scandinavian-currencies-lead-rebound-vs-struggling-dollar.html|title=FOREX-Scandinavian currencies lead rebound vs struggling dollar|first=Saikat|last=Chatterjee|date=10 September 2018|publisher=CNBC}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/europe/sweden-faces-government-deadlock-as-far-right-gains/articleshow/65755563.cms|title=Sweden faces government deadlock as far-right gains|newspaper=The Times of India}}</ref><ref name=\"WarOfIdeas\">{{cite magazine | last1=Schultheis | first1=Emily | title=Sweden's Far Right Has Won the War of Ideas | url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2018/09/10/swedens-nazi-offspring-won-the-war-of-ideas/ | date=10 September 2018 | magazine=[[Foreign Policy]] | accessdate=11 September 2018}}</ref> Regardless, the party became the largest in two constituencies in southern region [[Sk\u00e5ne County|Scania]] and topped the polls in 21 out of 33 Scanian municipalities and in 31 out of 290 municipalities overall.<ref name=val2018/> The voter turnout of 87.18%<ref name=val2018>{{cite web|url=https://data.val.se/val/val2018/slutresultat/R/rike/index.html|title=R\u00f6ster - Val 2018|website=data.val.se|accessdate=18 January 2019}}</ref> was the highest in 33 years and 1.38 percentage points higher than the [[2014 Swedish general election|2014 elections]]. A record 26 out of 29 constituencies returned a [[hung parliament]].<ref name=val2018/>\n\nFollowing the elections, Prime Minister [[Stefan L\u00f6fven]] lost a vote of no-confidence on 25 September, forcing a parliamentary vote on a new government. In the meantime, [[L\u00f6fven I Cabinet|his government]] remained in power as a [[caretaker government]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Speaker [[Andreas Norl\u00e9n]] nominated Moderate leader [[Ulf Kristersson]] to form a government on 9 November. However, Kristersson lost a vote to confirm him in office by a margin of 154\u2013195. He was supported by his own Moderate Party, the Christian Democrats and the Sweden Democrats, despite having outruled this scenario before the election, but the Liberals and the Centre Party, the other parties in the centre-right Alliance, were not willing to form a government reliant on the Sweden Democrats.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.dn.se/nyheter/politik/sd-rostar-ja-till-kristersson/|title=SD r\u00f6star ja till Kristersson som statsminister - DN.SE|last=Tenitskaja|first=Mia Holmgren, Alexandra Carlsson|date=13 November 2018|work=DN.SE|access-date=2018-11-13|language=sv-se}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.dn.se/nyheter/politik/sanningens-minut-for-kristerssons-tankta-regering/|title=Nu avg\u00f6rs Kristerssons statsminister\u00f6de - DN.SE|last=Tenitskaja|first=Alexandra Carlsson|date=14 November 2018|work=DN.SE|access-date=2018-11-14|language=sv-se}}</ref> On 15 November, Norl\u00e9n invited Centre Party leader [[Annie L\u00f6\u00f6f]] to try to form a government, but she was unable to do so. Norl\u00e9n then nominated L\u00f6fven, but following unsuccessful negotiations with the Centre Party and the Liberals he lost a confirmation vote 116\u2013200 on 14 December.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dn.se/nyheter/politik/0900-lofven-provas-av-riksdagen/|title=Riksdagen r\u00f6star nej till Stefan L\u00f6fven (S) som statsminister|date=14 December 2018|website=DN.SE|language=sv|access-date=2018-12-14}}</ref>\n\nHours after the failed vote to confirm L\u00f6fven, Norl\u00e9n announced that he would be meeting with representatives of the [[Election Authority (Sweden)|Election Authority]] regarding a potential extraordinary election. The Speaker also stated that he would be engaging in talks with the parties during the weekend and that he would present the next phase of the government formation process by the following week.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dn.se/nyheter/politik/efter-beslutet-talmannen-forbereder-ett-eventuellt-extraval/|title=Talmannen Andreas Norl\u00e9n f\u00f6rbereder ett eventuellt extraval|date=14 December 2018|website=DN.SE|language=sv|access-date=2018-12-14}}</ref> L\u00f6fven was finally re-elected with a 115\u2013153 result as Prime Minister on 18 January 2019 after the Social Democrats struck an [[L\u00f6fven II Cabinet#January agreement|agreement]] with the Greens, the Liberals, and the Centre Party;<ref name=\"thelocal.se\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thelocal.se/20190118/stefan-lofven-voted-back-in-as-swedish-prime-minister|title=Stefan L\u00f6fven voted back in as Swedish prime minister|date=18 January 2019|website=www.thelocal.se|accessdate=18 January 2019}}</ref> and after the Left Party reluctantly agreed to abstain from voting against L\u00f6fven.<ref name=\"thelocal.se\"/> Due to Sweden's principle of negative parliamentarism this result was enough, as less than the majority of the parliament voted against him, while the supporting parties abstained.\n\nWith the [[L\u00f6fven II Cabinet|government]] being down to 116 seats (59 short of a majority), this rendered it the government with the lowest electoral support to begin a term in Swedish history and forced to approve several liberal policy platforms the government had campaigned against.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/detta-vet-vi-om-s-mp-l-och-c-uppgorelsen|title=Uppg\u00f6relsen mellan S, MP, L och C - punkt f\u00f6r punkt|publisher=[[Sveriges Television|SVT]]|language=sv|date=21 March 2019|accessdate=28 January 2020}}</ref> With the right-wing opposition having 154 seats, to the coalition and confidence and supply agreements' 167 and the Left Party's 28, it still rendered a hung parliament even after the government formation, which exposed the government to high-profile losses in parliament.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.expressen.se/nyheter/m-kd-och-v-ar-overens-/|title=Oppositionen \u00e4r \u00f6verens - vill ge 7,5 miljarder till v\u00e4lf\u00e4rden|language=sv|publisher=[[Expressen]]|date=22 January 2020|accessdate=28 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Context==\n\n===2014 budget crisis===\nJust two months after having formed a minority government, Prime Minister Stefan L\u00f6fven announced on the afternoon of 3 December 2014 that he intended to make the formal arrangements for calling an extraordinary election on 29 December 2014 \u2013 the earliest date permitted by the constitution.\n\nThe election seemed to be necessary after L\u00f6fven's Social Democrat-led government lost a vote on the budget by 182 to 153, owing to the Sweden Democrats voting with the opposition, leading to a [[2014 Swedish government crisis|cabinet crisis]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-30306992 Sweden election called by L\u00f6fven after parliament defeat] BBC News, 3 December 2014</ref> It would have been the first early election since [[1958 Swedish general election|1958]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.svd.se/naringsliv/svd-live-regeringskrisen-onsdag-e-m_4160367.svd|title=Just nu: Regeringskrisen forts\u00e4tter|website=SvD.se|accessdate=3 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nHowever, an agreement between the Social Democrats, the Greens, the Moderates, the Centrists, the Liberals and the Christian Democrats was signed on 26 December 2014, outlining a series of conditions in order to ensure political stability until at least 2022.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.socialdemokraterna.se/upload/%C3%96verenskommelse.pdf |title=Agreement |access-date=27 December 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141227110718/http://www.socialdemokraterna.se/upload/%C3%96verenskommelse.pdf |archive-date=27 December 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The agreement included two main provisions:\n\n*The candidate for Prime Minister who gathered the most support would be elected. This would apply to both incumbent and new candidates for PM.\n*A government in minority would be allowed to have its budget passed, by the abstention of opposition parties who had signed the agreement.\n\nAfter negotiations between the Government and the Alliance for Sweden concluded, the snap election was called off on 27 December 2014. On 9 October 2015, following the Christian Democrats' departure from the agreement, the December 2014 agreement was dissolved. However, the Moderates, the Centrists and the Liberals allowed the Social Democrats minority government to continue to govern.\n\n==Campaign issues==\nIn May 2018, the issues that the Swedish voters considered most important were [[Immigration to Sweden|immigration]], [[Healthcare in Sweden|healthcare]] and [[Social integration|integration]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.expressen.se/nyheter/val-2018/ny-matning-de-ar-viktigaste-valfragorna/ |title=Ny m\u00e4tning: De \u00e4r viktigaste valfr\u00e5gorna |language=sv-SE |access-date=2018-09-14}}</ref> In the days leading up to the election, the most important issue was the environment, followed by immigration and health care.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.expressen.se/nyheter/val-2018/ny-matning-de-ar-viktigaste-valfragorna/ |title=Klimatet upp i topp som v\u00e4ljarnas viktigaste fr\u00e5ga |language=sv-SE |access-date=2018-09-14}}</ref> With the polls showing that the Sweden Democrats could be [[kingmaker]]s there was speculation over possible government coalitions.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.neweurope.eu/article/far-right-momentum-sweden-bolsters-chances-grand-coalition-government/ |title=Far-right momentum in Sweden bolsters the chances of a grand coalition government |date=24 May 2018 |website=New Europe |language=en-US |access-date=2018-09-14}}</ref>\n\nConcerns about foreign influence in the election were raised by the [[Swedish Security Service]] and others, leading to various countermeasures.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/ahead-election-sweden-warns-voters-foreign-disinformation/story?id=57694373 |title=Ahead of election, Sweden warns its voters against foreign disinformation |last=News |first=A. B. C. |date=10 September 2018 |website=ABC News |language=en |access-date=2018-09-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thelocal.se/20180222/sweden-warns-of-certain-foreign-powers-meddling-in-the-2018-election |title=Sweden warns of 'certain foreign powers' meddling in the 2018 election |date=22 February 2018 |language=en |access-date=2018-09-14}}</ref>\n\nThe summer of 2018 saw several violent incidents occur, including the arson of over 100 cars on 15 August, which may have caused 10% of Swedes to state that \"law and order\" is the key issue in the upcoming election.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news |last1=Anderson |first1=Christina |title=More Than 100 Cars Burned in Mass Arson Attack in Sweden |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/15/world/europe/sweden-car-fires.html |accessdate=17 August 2018 |newspaper=The New York Times |language=en}}</ref>{{Additional citation needed|date=October 2018}} While Sweden has faced sporadic gang violence in recent years at the end of summer break for students, violence in [[Gothenburg]], [[Falkenberg]] and [[Trollh\u00e4ttan]] was said to be on a larger scale.<ref name=\"Reuters\">{{cite news |last1=Editorial |first1=Reuters |title=Youths in Swedish towns burn and vandalize scores of cars |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-sweden-violence/youths-in-swedish-towns-burn-and-vandalize-scores-of-cars-idUSKBN1KZ0OJ |accessdate=17 August 2018 |work=U.S. |publisher=Reuters |date=14 August 2018}}</ref> Prime Minister L\u00f6fven referred to the August violence as if it was organized \"almost like a military operation\".<ref name=\"Reuters\"/> In the following days, Twitter accounts connected to Russia tweeted about the fires, according to the [[Alliance for Securing Democracy]] intending to influence English-language readers.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/inrikes/kremlkopplade-twitterkonton-utnyttjar-bilbranderna-for-att-paverka-opinionen-i-usa |title=Experten: Kremlkopplade Twitterkonton utnyttjade bilbr\u00e4nder f\u00f6r att p\u00e5verka opinionen i USA |last=Nyheter |first=SVT |date=7 September 2018 |website=SVT Nyheter |language=sv |access-date=2018-09-16}}</ref> According to the [[Oxford Internet Institute]], eight of the top 10 \"junk news\" sources during the election campaign were Swedish, and \"Russian sources comprised less than 1% of the total number of URLs shared in the data sample.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Fake News Takes Its Toll on Sweden\u2019s Elections |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2018-11-15/fake-news-roiled-sweden-s-elections-but-it-was-homegrown |publisher=Bloomberg |date=15 November 2018}}</ref> Non-Swedish media frequently emphasize the events in order to advance a narrative of a society in decay, along with some negative but restricted reporting around immigration, to describe great gains by the Sweden Democrats; this has been criticized as a \"false narrative\" and \"misreporting\" by domestic media.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://via.tt.se/pressmeddelande/nya-narrativ-utmanar-omvarldens-bild-av-sverige?publisherId=153811&releaseId=2847417| title=Nya narrativ utmanar omv\u00e4rldens bild av Sverige |trans-title=New narratives challenge the outside world's picture of Sweden| publisher=[[Swedish Institute]]| date=18 June 2018| accessdate=9 June 2018 |language=sv}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://sverigesradio.se/sida/artikel.aspx?programid=83&artikel=7032976| title=Osanningar om Sverige sprids i utl\u00e4ndsk media |trans-title=Untruths about Sweden are spread in foreign media| publisher=[[Sveriges Radio]]| date=31 August 2018| accessdate=9 August 2018 |language=sv}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.thelocal.se/20180907/sweden-election-misreported-abroad| title=Sweden's election is being misreported abroad \u2013 and this is a problem| website=[[The Local]]| date=7 September 2018| accessdate=9 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Contesting parties==\n{{Politics of Sweden|elections}}\n\n===Major parties===\nThe '''[[Swedish Social Democratic Party|Social Democratic Party]]''' (S; ''Socialdemokraterna'') was the largest political party in the Swedish [[Riksdag]], with 113 of the 349 seats. It was the major component of the incumbent [[L\u00f6fven I Cabinet|L\u00f6fven Cabinet]], in which it worked with the [[Green Party (Sweden)|Green Party]]. Its [[Party leader|leader]] [[Stefan L\u00f6fven]] had been [[Prime Minister of Sweden]] since 3 October 2014, and sought a mandate to continue his L\u00f6fven Cabinet.\n\nThe '''[[Moderate Party]]''' (M; ''Moderaterna'') was the second-largest party in the Riksdag with 84 seats. It was the largest governing party under [[Prime Minister of Sweden|Prime Minister]] [[Fredrik Reinfeldt]] from 2006 to 2014. The party was involved alongside three other parties in the [[Alliance (Sweden)|Alliance]]; all four sought to return to power together. Reinfeldt resigned as party leader after eight years as Prime Minister, and was succeeded as leader by [[Anna Kinberg Batra]] on 10 January 2015. Kinberg Batra's decision as the ''de facto'' leader to enter the budgetary procedure agreement with the left-of-centre cabinet saw sharp disgruntlement from some party districts. The Alliance had more MPs than the government parties, but still found itself in opposition. Owing to her low [[opinion poll]]ing numbers, Kinberg Batra faced internal pressure from multiple party districts and the [[Moderate Youth League]] to resign. She announced her resignation in a morning press conference on 25 August 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.aftonbladet.se/nyheter/a/bp8mv/efter-avgangskraven--akb-haller-presstraff-i-dag|title=Anna Kinberg Batra avg\u00e5r som partiledare f\u00f6r Moderaterna|work=Aftonbladet|access-date=26 August 2017}}</ref> Former prime minister and Moderate Party leader [[Carl Bildt]] was suggested as a replacement after Kinberg Batra resigned; however, despite some party districts supporting his candidacy, he declined the offer.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.aftonbladet.se/nyheter/a/ejq1O/carl-bildts-besked-om-partiledarfragan-inte-intresserad|title=Carl Bildts besked om partiledarfr\u00e5gan: Inte intresserad|work=Aftonbladet|access-date=2 October 2017}}</ref> Ultimately, Ulf Kristersson was elected to succeed Kinberg Batra as party leader, during an extra Moderate [[party conference]] on 1 October 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dn.se/nyheter/politik/ulf-kristersson-vill-gora-upp-med-s-om-invandringen/|title=Ulf Kristersson vill g\u00f6ra upp med S om invandringen&nbsp;\u2014 DN.SE|date=1 October 2017|work=DN.SE|access-date=2 October 2017|language=sv-se}}</ref>\n\nThe '''[[Sweden Democrats]]''' (SD; ''Sverigedemokraterna'') was the third-largest party in the Riksdag with 49 seats. In the [[2014 Swedish general election|2014 general election]] the party increased its number of seats by 29, becoming the third-largest party. Its leader was [[Jimmie \u00c5kesson]], who was the longest-serving party leader. The other Riksdag parties had repeatedly stated that they would not cooperate with the Sweden Democrats in a future government. An extra general election was called after the Sweden Democrats gave its support to the oppositional Alliance budget (see section '2014 budget crisis'). After the proposed extra election was cancelled, the party advertised itself as the 'only opposition party' and in the following months it saw a sharp rise in support (see section 'Opinion polls').\n\nThe '''[[Green Party (Sweden)|Green Party]]''' (MP; ''Milj\u00f6partiet'') was the fourth-largest party in the Riksdag with 25 seats. The Green Party was the minor component of the L\u00f6fven Cabinet, alongside the Social Democrats. It was the only Swedish party to have two [[spokesperson]]s, [[Gustav Fridolin]] (since 2011), who served as [[Minister for Education (Sweden)|Minister for Education]], and [[Isabella L\u00f6vin]] (since 2016), who served as [[Minister for International Development Cooperation (Sweden)|Minister for International Development Cooperation]]. This was the first time in Swedish history that the Green Party had its governmental record tested at an election.\n\nThe '''[[Centre Party (Sweden)|Centre Party]]''' (C; ''Centerpartiet'') was the fifth-largest party in the Riksdag with 22 seats. It was a part of the [[Reinfeldt Cabinet]] from 2006 to 2014, and was involved in the Alliance. The Centre Party had been led by [[Annie L\u00f6\u00f6f]] since 2011. It was subject to public attempts by L\u00f6fven to become a cooperation party, but the party traditionally leans towards the Moderate policy positions and stayed within the Alliance after the 2014 election.\n\nThe '''[[Left Party (Sweden)|Left Party]]''' (V; ''V\u00e4nsterpartiet'') was the sixth-largest party in the Riksdag with 21 seats. Its leader was [[Jonas Sj\u00f6stedt]]. He had said that the party sought to participate in a future [[Red-Greens (Sweden)|Red-Green coalition government]]. The Left Party did not support the L\u00f6fven Cabinet because it was not asked to participate in that cabinet following the 2014 general election, but supported its budget that was voted down on 3 December 2014. Following the budgetary agreement, the Left Party was what tips the left-of-centre minority into a larger minority than the Alliance.\n\nThe '''[[Liberals (Sweden)|Liberals]]''' (L; ''Liberalerna'') was the seventh-largest party in the Riksdag with 19 seats. It was a part of the Reinfeldt Cabinet from 2006 to 2014, and was involved in the Alliance. The Liberals had been led by [[Jan Bj\u00f6rklund]] since 2007; his leadership was being increasingly criticized within the party. Opinion polls in the year after the 2014 election suggested that the party was falling significantly behind and struggling to recapture its previous level of support. Having been in charge of the school system and integration of migrants, it came under a lot of criticism owing to falling school results and increased segregation in immigrant-dominated suburbs.\n\nThe '''[[Christian Democrats (Sweden)|Christian Democrats]]''' (KD; ''Kristdemokraterna'') had been led by [[Ebba Busch Thor]] since 2015. It was involved in the Alliance. Despite polling below the 4% electoral threshold for most of the time between the elections, the party saw a boost in support in the time period immediately prior to the election, guaranteeing its presence in the Riksdag (which was seen as essential in order for the Alliance to be able to form a government.). The party held on by a few tens of thousands of votes last time.\n\n=== Minor parties ===\nParties with less than 4% of the vote do not get any seats in the Riksdag.\n\n'''[[Feminist Initiative (Sweden)|Feminist Initiative]]''' (FI; ''Feministiskt Initiativ''), led by former Left Party leader [[Gudrun Schyman]], was the country's ninth-largest party, and was represented in the [[European Parliament]] following [[2014 European Parliament election in Sweden|the 2014 European election]]. The party received 0.4% of the vote in the election, compared to 3% in the previous election 2014.\n\nThe '''[[Pirate Party (Sweden)|Pirate Party]]''' (PP; ''Piratpartiet'') [[2009 European Parliament election in Sweden|won representation in the 2009\u201314 European Parliament]], but its subsequent runs for office had been less successful. It has been mentioned in some polls as the tenth-largest party, but appeared to be far from having a chance to break the threshold at a domestic level.\n\nThe '''[[Alternative for Sweden]]''' (''Alternativ f\u00f6r Sverige)'' was a party with no representation in the Riksdag. It was formed from members expelled from the Sweden Democrats in 2015, and was led by [[Gustav Kasselstrand]]. The party received 0.3% of the vote, and thus failed to enter the [[Riksdag]] in this election.\n\n==Electoral system==\nThe Swedish Riksdag is made up of 349 MPs, and all are elected through [[open list]] [[proportional representation]] on multi-member party lists that are either regional (most major parties) or national (Sweden Democrats). Each of the 29 constituencies has a set number of parliamentarians that is divided through constituency results to ensure regional representation. The other MPs are then elected through a proportional balancing, to ensure that the numbers of elected MPs for the various parties accurately represent the votes of the electorate. The Swedish constitution (''Regeringsformen'') 1 Ch. 4 \u00a7 says that the Riksdag is responsible for taxation and making laws, and 1 Ch. 6 \u00a7 says that the government is held responsible to the Riksdag. This means that Sweden has [[Parliamentary system|parliamentarism]] in a [[constitutional monarchy]]\u2014ensuring that the government is responsible to the people's representatives. A minimum of 4% of the national vote is required for a party to enter the Riksdag, alternatively 12% or more within a constituency.\n\n=== Vote secrecy and party-specific ballots ===\nElection officials are responsible for party-specific ballot papers being present in the voting places for parties that have obtained more than one percent of the votes in the previous parliamentary election.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.val.se/servicelankar/other-languages/english-engelska/putting-out-ballot-papers.html |title=Putting out ballot papers |date=20 April 2018 |publisher=Valmyndigheten |access-date=10 September 2018}}</ref> If there is no access to the wanted party-specific ballot paper, a voter may cast a vote by writing in the party name of choice on a blank ballot paper.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.val.se/servicelankar/other-languages/english-engelska/ballot-papers.html |title=Ballot papers |date=17 August 2018 |publisher=Valmyndigheten |access-date=10 September 2018}}</ref> The voter generally chooses a party-specific ballot in the open and only then marks the ballot they chose in the [[voting booth]].<ref name=\"Bolling0\"/>\n\nThe OSCE Office for Democratic Institutions and Human Rights sent an election expert team of two members to the 2018 general election to examine and assess this system, including in relation to questions of the secrecy of the ballot. The observers are to issue a report eight weeks after the election was held.<ref name=\"Bolling0\">{{cite news |last=Bolling |first=Anders |date=9 September 2018 |title=Utl\u00e4ndska observat\u00f6rer granskar valsedlar som ligger \u00f6ppet |url=https://www.dn.se/nyheter/politik/utlandska-observatorer-granskar-valsedlar-som-ligger-oppet/ |work=Dagens Nyheter |language=Swedish |access-date=10 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe neo-nazi organisation [[Nordic Resistance Movement]] was reported shouting slogans and filming voters in several election rooms.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.aftonbladet.se/nyheter/a/L0E3d4/nmr-skrek-slagord-i-vallokal | title = NMR skrek slagord i vallokal | newspaper=Aftonbladet | accessdate=17 September 2018|date=9 September 2018|language=sv}}</ref>\n\nThere were reports of missing party-specific ballots in some voting districts during the early voting phase.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sj\u00f6gren |first=Alf |date=22 August 2018 |title=F\u00f6rtidsr\u00f6stningen f\u00f6rsenad \u2013 valsedlar saknas i m\u00e5nga lokaler |url=https://www.sydsvenskan.se/2018-08-22/fortidsrostning-forsenad-valsedlar-saknas-i-manga-lokaler |work=Sydsvenskan |language=Swedish |access-date=10 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Eriksson |first=Lisa |date=23 August 2018 |title=Moderaternas valsedlar f\u00f6rsvunna |url=http://www.kuriren.nu/nyheter/moderaternas-valsedlar-forsvunna-nm4900207.aspx |work=Norrbottens-Kuriren |language=Swedish |access-date=10 September 2018}}</ref> On the election day, the Swedish public broadcaster [[Sveriges Television]] reported that the ballots of the Sweden Democrats were missing for 2 hours in one [[Gothenburg]] district.<ref>{{cite news |last=Josefsson |first=Helena |date=9 September 2018 |title=SD:s valsedlar saknades i vallokal |url=https://www.svt.se/nyheter/val2018/sd-s-valsedlar-saknades-i-vallokal |publisher=Sveriges Television |language=Swedish |access-date=10 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Parties==\nThe table below lists parties' 2014 representation in the [[Riksdag]].\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" colspan=\"3\"| Name\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Ideologies\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Leader\n! colspan=\"2\"| 2014 result\n|-\n! Votes (%)\n! Seats\n|-\n| style=\"background:{{Swedish Social Democratic Party/meta/color}};\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''S'''\n| [[Swedish Social Democratic Party]]<br />{{small|Socialdemokraterna}}\n| [[Social democracy]]\n| [[Stefan L\u00f6fven]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 31.0%\n| {{Composition bar|113|349|{{Swedish Social Democratic Party/meta/color}}}}\n|-\n| style=\"background:{{Moderate Party/meta/color}};\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''M'''\n| [[Moderate Party]]<br />{{small|Moderaterna}}\n| [[Liberal conservatism]]\n| [[Ulf Kristersson]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 23.3%\n| {{Composition bar|84|349|{{Moderate Party/meta/color}}}}\n|-\n| style=\"background:{{Sweden Democrats/meta/color}};\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''SD'''\n| [[Sweden Democrats]]<br />{{small|Sverigedemokraterna}}\n| [[Right-wing populism]]<br />\n| [[Jimmie \u00c5kesson]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 12.9%\n| {{Composition bar|49|349|{{Sweden Democrats/meta/color}}}}\n|-\n| style=\"background:{{Green Party (Sweden)/meta/color}};\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''MP'''\n| [[Green Party (Sweden)|Green Party]]<br />{{small|Milj\u00f6partiet}}\n| [[Green politics]]\n| [[Isabella L\u00f6vin]]<br />[[Gustav Fridolin]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 6.9%\n| {{Composition bar|25|349|{{Green Party (Sweden)/meta/color}}}}\n|-\n| style=\"background:{{Centre Party (Sweden)/meta/color}};\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''C'''\n| [[Centre Party (Sweden)|Centre Party]]<br />{{small|Centerpartiet}}\n| [[Liberalism]]<br />[[Nordic agrarianism|Agrarianism]]\n| [[Annie L\u00f6\u00f6f]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 6.1%\n| {{Composition bar|22|349|{{Centre Party (Sweden)/meta/color}}}}\n|-\n| style=\"background:{{Left Party (Sweden)/meta/color}};\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''V'''\n| [[Left Party (Sweden)|Left Party]]<br />{{small|V\u00e4nsterpartiet}}\n| [[Socialism]]\n| [[Jonas Sj\u00f6stedt]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 5.7%\n| {{Composition bar|21|349|{{Left Party (Sweden)/meta/color}}}}\n|-\n| style=\"background:{{Liberals (Sweden)/meta/color}};\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''L'''\n| [[Liberals (Sweden)|Liberals]]<br />{{small|Liberalerna}}\n| [[Liberalism]]\n| [[Jan Bj\u00f6rklund]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 5.4%\n| {{Composition bar|19|349|{{Liberals (Sweden)/meta/color}}}}\n|-\n| style=\"background:{{Christian Democrats (Sweden)/meta/color}};\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''KD'''\n| [[Christian Democrats (Sweden)|Christian Democrats]]<br />{{small|Kristdemokraterna}}\n| [[Christian democracy]]\n| [[Ebba Busch Thor]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 4.6%\n| {{Composition bar|16|349|{{Christian Democrats (Sweden)/meta/color}}}}\n|}\n\n==Opinion polls==\n{{main|Opinion polling for the Swedish general election, 2018}}\n[[File:Swedish Opinion Polling, 30 Day Moving Average, 2014-2018.png|30-day moving average of poll results from September 2014 to the election in 2018, with each line corresponding to a political party.]]\n\n==Results==\n{{main|Results of the 2018 Swedish general election}}\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:right\n|-\n|colspan=7|[[File:Sveriges riksdag 20180924 enwp.svg|center|300px]]\n|-\n!colspan=3|Party\n!Votes\n!%\n!Seats\n!+/\u2212\n|-\n|bgcolor={{Swedish Social Democratic Party/meta/color}}| ||align=left|[[Swedish Social Democratic Party|Social Democratic Party]]||align=center|S||1,830,386||28.26||100||\u221213\n|-\n|bgcolor={{Moderate Party/meta/color}}| ||align=left|[[Moderate Party]]||align=center|M||1,284,698||19.84||70||\u221214\n|-\n|bgcolor={{Sweden Democrats/meta/color}}| ||align=left|[[Sweden Democrats]]||align=center|SD||1,135,627||17.53||62||+13\n|-\n|bgcolor={{Centre Party (Sweden)/meta/color}}| ||align=left|[[Centre Party (Sweden)|Centre Party]]||align=center|C||557,500||8.61||31||+9\n|-\n|bgcolor={{Left Party (Sweden)/meta/color}}| ||align=left|[[Left Party (Sweden)|Left Party]]||align=center|V||518,454||8.00||28||+7\n|-\n|bgcolor={{Christian Democrats (Sweden)/meta/color}}| ||align=left|[[Christian Democrats (Sweden)|Christian Democrats]]||align=center|KD||409,478||6.32||22||+6\n|-\n|bgcolor={{Liberals (Sweden)/meta/color}}| ||align=left|[[Liberals (Sweden)|Liberals]]||align=center|L||355,546||5.49||20||+1\n|-\n|bgcolor={{Green Party (Sweden)/meta/color}}| ||align=left|[[Green Party (Sweden)|Green Party]]||align=center|MP||285,899||4.41||16||\u22129\n|-\t\n!c